  "why": "The paper’s approach enforces semantic consistency (when applicable) and actively constrains naturalness/conformity of mutated inputs. Semantic consistency is enforced by designing mutations in the interpretation domain, requiring applicability preconditions, and producing a matching mutated interpretation (i.e., the oracle expects Percep(δ_r(r)) == δ_interp(interp)). Naturalness is enforced by restricting mutations to real-world resources (entities extracted from a prior dataset) and by multiple conformity checks (perspective/vanishing-point matching, placement on the road, and lighting similarity checks). The implementation therefore produces mutations that preserve semantics and aim to remain realistic within the domain rather than generating unconstrained, unrealistic distortions.",
  "evidence": "Page 1960, Section 3.2 \"Semantic Mutations with semSensFuzz\": \"First, we scope the space of all mutations Δ based on the entities that appear in the interps of the available tests... Second, we associate a set of preconditions Prec with each mutation δ, specified in terms of the interp that defines whether δ is applicable to a given t. If Prec(interp) is not satisfied, then δ is not applicable to that test... Third, we enable the parameterization of δ_r to employ real sensor data to increase the likelihood of conformity. For example, when adding a car... then δ_addCar_r could put the car from r_j into r_i.\" \n\nPage 1960, Section 3.1 \"Problem definition\": \"We say that Percep passes a mutated test case δ(t), if and only if Percep(δ_r(r)) = δ_interp(interp), highlighting the symmetry of the mutation functions. ... At a conceptual level, our approach thus constitutes a form of metamorphic testing...\" \n\nPage 1963, Section 4.3.1 \"Implementation\": \"We add the constraint that the entity must be placed at the same relative physical coordinates to the camera in the new test case as it was in the source test case... we divide the images into quadrants and consider two images to be compatible if their vanishing points are in the same quadrant... if the entity does not have a median value within 5 units (~2%) of the median value of the base image target area, then it fails the conformity check.\" \n\nPage 1961, Section 4.1 \"semImFuzz Architecture\": \"semImFuzz requires a prior data set as a basis for mutation... As a preprocessing step, semImFuzz parses the prior test set to build a resource set of available data, e.g. a list of all cars and their poses.\""
